Basic concepts of Grammer of Graphics

  • gg in ggplot means: Grammer of Graphics
  • Grammer of Graphics is about mapping data points to aesthetic attributes (colour, shape, size) of geometric objects (points, lines, bars)
  • Thus, ggplot works with dataframes and not individual vectors and maps data from the dataframe to parts of the plot (aesthetics)
  • You can keep enhancing the plot by adding more layers
  • basic syntax: ggplot(data = NULL, mapping = aes()) + geom_xyz()
    • where you provide the dataframe to the data argument
    • and tell the mapping argument how to map columns of your dataframe to certain parts of your plot
    • Note that the mapping arguments value should be wrapped in the aes() (aesthetics) function. This tells the ggplot function which parts of the plot should be the mapped to the dataframe. Plot aesthetics defined outside of aes() will be constants. (Take a look at the examples and come back here again after to make sure you understood.)
  • type ?ggplot to your console to learn more about the arguments

Basic plot

    ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut)) +
        geom_point()

Layers (you can do the same thing in different ways)

    ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut)) +
        geom_point() +
        geom_smooth()

and

    ggplot(diamonds) +
        geom_point(aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut)) +
        geom_smooth(aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut))

are the same.

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
